{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:29:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1061"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1061"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.18,0.13,0.05,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88206"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38762"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 56-year-old woman presents after an episode of upper abdominal pain. The pain came on suddenly, lasted about 30 minutes and then settled. She does not take any medications. She has a 15 pack-year smoking history and drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is normal. An ultrasound examination is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver cysts","Haemangioma","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Metastatic deposits","Hydatid disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere could be many explanations for this patient\u0027s symptoms and it is quite likely that this investigation was arranged because the medical practitioner was thinking about gallstones and an episode of biliary colic. The gallbladder is not shown in the image, but there is a clear view of the liver. Within the liver substance are several well defined fluid-filled structures, the largest being about 8 cm in length. These are simple \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver cysts\u003C/strong\u003E. Liver cysts are found in some 15% of the population. They are usually incidental findings and of a benign nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid cysts \u003C/strong\u003Etypically have a calcified rim and whilst they also tend to be incidental findings, these cysts are now uncommon in the Australian population, but still can be found in sheep rearing parts of the country. They are more likely to be seen in migrants from parts of the world where hydatid disease is endemic, such as the Middle East.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbsence of visible vascularity makes the less less likely to be an\u003Cstrong\u003E haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic deposits \u003C/strong\u003Ewould normally be of similar density to the rest of the liver, whereas the lesion shown is an hepatic cyst, which appears as a clearly circumscribed anechoic lesion with an increase in the through transmission of sound and no nodularity within the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAreas of \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E are not usually well-marginated and are usually isoechoic with the surrounding liver tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most liver cysts are usually incidental findings."],"references":["Mavilia MG, Pakala T, Molina M, et al. Differentiating cystic liver lesions: a review of imaging modalities, diagnosis and management. J Clin Transl Hepatol 2018; 6:208\u201316."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88206"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1061"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19645"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19645"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/384b73f6-e347-48dc-8e67-33622312a127.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/384b73f6-e347-48dc-8e67-33622312a127.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":571,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88206"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-12T21:00:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T21:00:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags